# Planning

## Co-design with the user

- All tasks are planned and co-designed with the user — align on every high-level and
  important decision before substantial execution.
- Get early feedback when the task is ambiguous, high-risk, or wide in scope; otherwise
  proceed after just enough inspection to form a concrete plan.
- When a specific decision needs your input, compare the alternatives in a trade-off
  table — not a questionnaire — so they're easy to weigh side by side.

## Review the plan

- Before presenting a plan to the user, have a fresh sub-agent review it using
  `my-code-review`; address its findings first.
- After the user's review and iteration, if there were significant changes, run the
  fresh-sub-agent `my-code-review` pass again before proceeding to implementation.

## Research before building

- Before planning a custom solution, research existing, reusable solutions and prioritize
  them. Prefer adopting or extending over reinventing.

## Solution preferences

- Prefer solutions idiomatic to the problem space, framework, system, and technology.
- Prefer general solutions that improve long-term maintainability over quick one-offs.
- Prefer declarative design over imperative.

## Documentation

- Decide what documentation to create or update for the change (READMEs, design docs,
  runbooks, inline comments) and plan it as work.

## Break into testable phases

- Break the implementation into concrete, usable functionality that can be programmatically
  tested and verified at each step/phase — each phase is a complete definition including
  its own validation (linting, tests, build/compile, manual checks).
- Plan an automated, persistent test suite that validates the whole implemented
  functionality and catches regressions over time — a hard requirement (see `my-testing`).

## Format & template

- Keep plans concise and scannable: clean Markdown hierarchy (headings, tables, bullet
  lists), not dense prose or confusing sub-numbering (`1a`, `1b`).
- Use this template (inspired by tech design docs):

```markdown
# <Title>

## Context & Problem
The problem/need, what prompted it, and the intended outcome.

## Goals & non-goals
What this addresses — and what it explicitly does not.

## Approach
The proposed design and why it fits (idiomatic, declarative, maintainable).

## Alternatives considered
Design alternatives weighed, each with the reasoning for rejecting it.

## Implementation plan
Ordered, concrete phases. Each phase is a complete definition including its own
validation (linting, tests, build/compile, manual checks).

## Documentation
Docs to create or update for the change (READMEs, design docs, runbooks, inline comments).

## Test Coverage
Visualize the persistent, automated test coverage planned (e.g. a functionality × test-type
matrix) and identify any gaps. Any missing or manual-only coverage must state explicit reasoning.

## Risks & open decisions
Known risks; decisions still needing alignment (compare each as a trade-off table when seeking input).
```
